{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[G4 child-consistency — container review of parent 1f19-adf2-ffb2-4b09 paired with THIS child (S5 b7fa: Surface the ref + source controls on the CLI and MCP tool schemas)]\n\nRan the 7 cross-child interaction modes for this surface child against the WHOLE sibling roster (S1 6d56, S2 70c7, S3 fa49, S4 30b3, S6 1ba5). One high-confidence finding (scope overlap / dependency gap at the S3↔S5 code-review surface seam); the other 6 modes are clean under the high-confidence / benign-reading filter.\n\nFINDING (scope overlap + dependency gap — the existing review_code base/head (+ --diff-file) surface is left unreconciled with the new single-`ref` control; neither S3 nor S5 owns retiring it on the SURFACE)\n- finding: The parent collapses code-review to a SINGLE ref (\"Diff-base (base+head) handling for code-review ... code-review gets a single repo copy at a single ref in this epic\"). S3 (fa49) owns that change at the BEHAVIOR level (What: \"Every operation takes ONE ref and gets ONE snapshot (code-review included; no base+head pair in this epic)\"; AC3: \"code-review uses a single snapshot at a single ref (no base+head pair) like the others\"). THIS child (S5) owns the SURFACE and its What only says ADD `ref`+`source` to `review_code` (CLI `code-review` + MCP `review_code`) — it is SILENT on REMOVING/reconciling the pre-existing `base`/`head` (and CLI `--diff-file`) parameters those surfaces carry today. Result: as decomposed, S5 ADDS a single `--ref`/`ref` while the existing diff-range controls remain, leaving `review_code` advertising BOTH a single-ref snapshot control AND a base..head diff-range pair on the same surface — two contradictory code-selection controls on one tool, with no child claiming the retirement on the surface side.\n- criteria: this child (S5) AC1 (\"Every code-reading CLI command accepts --ref and --source with the documented defaults\") + AC2 (\"Every code-reading MCP tool accepts ref + source\"); S3 (fa49) AC3 (single snapshot at a single ref, no base+head pair); parent Out-of-scope clause (\"code-review gets a single repo copy at a single ref ... like every other operation\").\n- location: S5 (b7fa) What bullets 1-2 (CLI `code-review` + MCP `review_code` gain ref/source) + Scope (\"Out: the underlying behavior (S1-S4)\"); S3 (fa49) What (\"code-review included; no base+head pair\") + Scope (\"Out: ... CLI/MCP surface schemas (S5)\"); parent Out-of-scope (diff-base handling).\n- evidence:\n  1. Existing MCP `review_code` signature is a DIFF RANGE, not a single ref: src/rebar/mcp_server.py:595-599 — `def review_code(base: str = \"HEAD~1\", head: str = \"HEAD\", reviewers: list[str] | None = None)`. S5's \"add ref+source to review_code\" does not say what becomes of `base`/`head`.\n  2. Existing CLI `rebar review-code` carries `--base`/`--head` AND `--diff-file`: src/rebar/_cli/_llm_commands.py:83-85 (`--base` default HEAD~1, `--head` default HEAD, `--diff-file`). S5's \"add --ref/--source to ... code-review\" does not say what becomes of `--base`/`--head`/`--diff-file`.\n  3. S3 claims the single-ref BEHAVIOR collapse (its AC3) but explicitly scopes the surface OUT (\"Out: ... CLI/MCP surface schemas (S5)\") — so S3 does not retire the base/head SCHEMA/FLAGS.\n  4. S5 claims the SURFACE but its What only ADDS ref/source and explicitly scopes the underlying behavior OUT (\"Out: the underlying behavior (S1-S4)\") — so S5 does not state the base/head retirement either.\n  5. Roster-wide: no sibling's What/AC mentions removing/retiring/reconciling `base`/`head`/`--diff-file` on the code-review surface (search for \"base+head\"/\"diff-file\" finds only the existing CLI/tests/docs, no child obligation). The surface-side retirement is owned by neither S3 nor S5.\n- scenarios: (a) Implementer ships S5 by ADDING `ref`/`source` to `review_code` while leaving `base`/`head`/`--diff-file` in place → the tool advertises a single-ref snapshot control alongside a base..head diff pair; an agent/human can pass `--ref X --base A --head B` and the schema gives no defined precedence — exactly the kind of ambiguous client-facing control the \"client-specified ... exact code version\" success-criterion is meant to make crisp. (b) Implementer reads parent + S3 and DROPS base/head on the surface, but since that retirement is in NEITHER child's stated scope it lands as undocumented surface-breakage (callers/tests at tests/interfaces/store/test_llm_optionality.py:126 use `review-code --diff-file`) with no child AC covering the migration. Either way S5 AC1/AC2 (\"every code-reading command/tool accepts ref+source\") is satisfiable while the code-review surface remains internally contradictory or silently broken.\n- impact: The S3 (behavior: single ref) ↔ S5 (surface: schema/flags) seam leaves the base/head→single-ref RECONCILIATION ON THE SURFACE unowned. S5's AC1/AC2 only ADD ref/source; nothing in S5 (or S3, which scopes the surface out) retires/reconciles the pre-existing base/head/diff-file controls on `review_code`, so the parent's \"single ref for code-review like every other operation\" is not cleanly realized on the client surface this child owns.\n- checklist_item: scope overlap / dependency gap (cross-child modes 4 + 3) at the S3↔S5 code-review surface seam\n- suggested_fix: Make the surface-side retirement explicit and assign it. Preferred: extend THIS child (S5) with a What bullet + AC stating that `review_code`/`rebar review-code` REPLACE `base`/`head` (and resolve/retire `--diff-file`) with the single `--ref`/`ref` control (or define explicit precedence + deprecation), so the code-review surface exposes exactly one code-selection control consistent with S3's single-snapshot behavior. Cross-reference S3 AC3 so the behavior-and-surface halves of the base+head→single-ref collapse are jointly owned. (Symmetrically, S3 could name the surface retirement and hand it to S5 — but the obligation must live in one of the two by name.)\n\nClean on the other 6 modes:\n- implicit shared state: the ref/source/verified_at_sha chain is a consistent producer→consumer flow — S1 resolves the immutable SHA, S3 threads it + re-roots, S4 records/signs verified_at_sha, THIS child surfaces ref/source + verified_at_sha on CLI/MCP, S6 documents the semantics + origin/main default. No surfaced value lacks a producer; defaults (origin/main) agree across S3/S5/S6.\n- conflicting assumptions: attested-default-still-signs (this child AC3) and local-reflected-as-unsigned (this child AC4) agree with S3 (marks local unsigned, AC2), S4 (bars local signing, AC2), and S6 (documents attested-signs/local-never-signs). No contradiction.\n- ordering violation: logical S1→S3→S4→this-child ordering; all six children carry empty deps uniformly and parent AC8 only requires all-closed + green, so no encoded ordering is violated.\n- consumer impact: this child surfaces verified_at_sha (produced by S4) and exposes ref/source (threaded by S3) — it consumes those contracts without redefining them; it produces no new behavior a sibling must adapt to. The REBAR_ROOT-semantics doc bullet (\"document that REBAR_ROOT only locates the object DB to fetch from\") is this child's own What plus prose delegated to S6 (S6 AC3 ref/source semantics) — a benign schema-text-vs-prose split, not a broken downstream contract; README.md:193/:261 already carry REBAR_ROOT in the MCP-setup block.\n- residual references: S1-S4 (Scope \"Out: the underlying behavior (S1-S4)\") and S6 (prose docs) all resolve to real roster siblings; the five named tool surfaces (review_plan/verify_completion/review_ticket/review_code/scan_spec) all exist in src/rebar/mcp_server.py. No dangling reference.\n\nNote (NOT a G4 finding on THIS pairing): the standing dependency-gap finding on sibling S4 (30b3) about routing the pinned-SHA snapshot handle into plan_review/attest.py's dependency_hashes()/_rehash()/claim-gate freshness re-check is a code seam between S3 and S4; it does not touch this surface child and is out of this pairing's scope.\n\nConclusion: one high-confidence cross-child inconsistency stands — the base/head (+ --diff-file) code-review SURFACE retirement that pairs with S3's single-ref behavior collapse is owned by neither S3 nor this child (scope-overlap/dependency-gap at the S3↔S5 seam). The remaining 6 modes are clean."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782521186063966001,"uuid":"846ce2b6-3a94-40c7-91f9-3fa8c1a986c7"}